pan class=\"eb\">might<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">must<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">ought to<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">shall<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">should<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">will<\/span> and <span class=\"eb\">would<\/span>. <span class=\"eb\">Dare<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">need<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">have to<\/span> and <span class=\"eb\">used to<\/span> also share some of the features of modal verbs.<\/li><li class=\"li\">Modal verbs have only one form. They have no <span class=\"ei\">-ing<\/span> or <span class=\"ei\">-ed<\/span> forms and do not add <span class=\"ei\">-s<\/span> to the 3rd person singular form:<ul class=\"examples\"><li class=\"\"><span class=\"unx\">He can speak three languages.<\/span><\/li><li class=\"\"><span class=\"unx\">She will try and visit tomorrow.<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">Modal verbs are followed by the infinitive of another verb without <span class=\"eb\">to<\/span>. The exceptions are <span class=\"eb\">ought to<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">have to<\/span> and <span class=\"eb\">used to<\/span>:<ul class=\"examples\"><li class=\"\"><span class=\"unx\">You must find a job.<\/span><\/li><li class=\"\"><span class=\"unx\">You ought to stop smoking.<\/span><\/li><li class=\"\"><span class=\"unx\">I used to smoke but I gave up two years ago.<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">Questions are formed without <span class=\"eb\">do<\/span>\/<span class=\"eb\">does<\/span> in the present, or <span class=\"eb\">did<\/span> in the past:<ul class=\"examples\"><li class=\"\"><span class=\"unx\">Can I invite Mary?<\/span><\/li><li class=\"\"><span class=\"unx\">Should I have invited Mary?<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">Negative sentences are formed with <span class=\"eb\">not<\/span> or the short form <span class=\"eb\">-n\u2019t<\/span> and do not use <span class=\"eb\">do<\/span>\/<span class=\"eb\">does<\/span> or <span class=\"eb\">did<\/span>.<\/li><\/ul><span class=\"p\">You will find m